
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `gp-display-html` baraye namayesh dadane file-haye HTML dar terminal estefade mishavad.  In dastoor HTML ra migirad va aan ra be shekle matni ke ghabl-khani bashad namayesh midahad.  

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `--version`  --> ℹ️  Namayesh dadane version dastoor.
    🔹 `--help`     --> ❓ Rahnamayi baraye estefade az dastoor va gozine-hayash.
    🔹 `<filename>` --> 📄 Name file HTML ke bayad namayesh dade shavad.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ gp-display-html page.html
    
    🔹 Namayesh dadane content file `page.html`.

    $ gp-display-html --help
    
    🔹 Namayesh dadane rahnama baraye dastoor.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ gp-display-html index.html

    🔹 Agar file `index.html` shamel matni mesl `<h1>Hello, world!</h1><p>This is a test page.</p>` bashad, terminal matne moratab shode ra namayesh midahad, hata agar namayeshe kamel HTML nabashad.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `gp-display-html` command is used to display HTML files in the terminal. It takes HTML as input and renders it into a readable text format.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `--version`  --> ℹ️  Display the command's version.
    🔹 `--help`     --> ❓ Show help information about the command and its options.
    🔹 `<filename>` --> 📄 The name of the HTML file to be displayed.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ gp-display-html page.html
    
    🔹 Display the content of the `page.html` file.

    $ gp-display-html --help
    
    🔹 Display the help information for the command.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ gp-display-html index.html

    🔹 If the `index.html` file contains text like `<h1>Hello, world!</h1><p>This is a test page.</p>`, the terminal will display a formatted text representation, though not a full HTML rendering.
